t 1349":"about 1349","1289":"1289","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1286":"1286","1285":"1285","1284":"1284","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Bredwardine, Herefordshire, England":"Bredwardine, Herefordshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Canteff-Selyff, Brecknock, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philippe, Alcee, Armand, Laurent, Leonce, Marcel, Yves, Clovis, Fernand, Gilberte, Janvier, Jean Claude.","Scottish, English, North German, French, Walloon, Catalan, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Rogero","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Cayetano, Jose, Silva.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Rogero</i> (see   Roger  ).","Catalan (<b>Rogeró</b>): from a pet form of the personal name   Roger  ."]},{"name":"Rieck","meanings":["South German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Ru(o)diger</i>, a compound of Old High German <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ (see   Roger  ).","North German: from a short form of a personal name containing the element <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Rjek</b>: nickname from Upper Sorbian <i>rjek</i> ‘hero’. Compare   Reck  ."]},{"name":"Rogelio","meanings":["Spanish; Portuguese (<b>Rogélio</b>): from the personal name <i>Rogelio</i>, Portuguese <i>Rogélio</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Roger  )."]},{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Roger  ."]},{"name":"Rogers","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Roger  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Ruaidhrí</b> (see   Rorie  ).","History: Thomas Rogers (<i>c.</i> 1587–1621), born in London, England, was among the Pilgrim Fathers who sailed on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620. He died during the first winter at Plymouth Colony, but his son Joseph survived and married, and was later joined in MA by his brother John. This name was subsequently brought to North America independently by many different bearers."]},{"name":"Rogel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Jose, Jose Luis, Juan, Marcos, Margarita, Wilfredo, Adilia, Alejandro, Ana Gladys, Ana Maria, Anacleto.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Rogel</i>, an equivalent of French   Roger  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rogelj</b>: nickname or topographic name from <i>rogelj</i> ‘horn, point’, figuratively ‘tall young man’, as a topographic name probably denoting someone who lived e.g. on a horn-shaped spur of a hill. The surname in the form <i>Rogel</i> is found in Slovenia, too, where it is a less common variant."]},{"name":"Prosser","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Rhosier</i> ‘son of Roger’ (see   Roger   and   Rosser  )."]},{"name":"Rogerson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Roger   + <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Ritger","meanings":["Altered form of German and Dutch <b>Rutger</b> or <b>Rütger</b>, from the personal name <i>Rudiger</i> (see   Roger  )."]},{"name":"Rogge","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Bernd, Bernhard, Elke, Hans, Helmut, Wolfgang.","German and Dutch: from a short form of the personal name   Roger  .","North German and Dutch: metonymic occupational name for a grower of rye or a baker of rye bread, from Low German, Dutch <i>rogge</i> ‘rye’."]}]},{"name":"Fawr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>fear(r)</i>, <i>farre</i> (Old English <i>fearr</i>) ‘steer, ox’, applied as a nickname for a fierce man or a metonymic occupational name for someone who kept a bull.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>varne</i>, <i>var</i>, with the same meaning as 1 above."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"Ieuanc","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger Ieuanc ap Roger Fawr was born in 1284, in Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Rosser Fawr ap Ieuan and Jane Baskerville. He married Joice Waldeboeff."},"et":{"1284–":"1284–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1349–1415":"1349–1415","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","–1289":"–1289","1415":"1415","1349":"1349","about 1349":"umbes 1349","1289":"1289","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1286":"1286"